{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1kahlo_ver01/data/sn83045462/0028060205A/1937111401/0738.xml":{"full_text":"INTERSTATE TRADE\nBARRIERS SCORED\nSales Taxes and Creation of State\nPorts of Entry Deplored by\nNew York Trust.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, Nov. 13 Preservation\nof the great free trade area represent\ned by continental United States is seri\nously threatened by the growth of bar\nriers to interstate commerce, says The\nIndex of the New York Trust Co.\nState sales taxes supplemented by\nUse taxes, chain store taxation, estab\nlishment of state ports of entry, the\nproposed Federal wages and hours bill,\nand the possible establishment of re\ngional authorities in seven flood-con\ntrol areas, are cited as actual or poten\nv tial obstacles to the unhampered flow\nOf commerce across state lines.\n\u201cWhile each one of the taxes, pro\nhibitions and proposed legislative acts\nmay have been actuated by worthy\nf motives and afford certain specific\nbenefits,\u201d The Index states, \"the broad\nnational interest has been obscured.\nIndividual states might feel compelled\nto produce locally substitutes for the\ngoods whose prices would be forced up\nby such measures.\n\u201cThe end would be a sectionalism\nequivalent to the nationalistic policies\nadopted by European countries to pro\ntect their industries from foreign\n..competition, over higher prices to be\npaid by the public, and the gradual\nbreakdown of the policy of liberalism\nand the nationwide free market which\nhave played such vital roles in our\nnational development.\u201d\n\ni CORPORATION\nREPORTS\nTRENDS AND PROSPECTS OF\nLEADING ORGANIZATIONS.\nNEW YORK. Nov. 13.\u2014The follow\n\u201elng Is today's summary of corporation\nhews, prepared by Standard Statistics\nCo Inc., New York:\nPackard Motor Car Co.\u2014Company\nIs reported to be planning to build a\nPacific Coast assembly plant at Los\nAngeles to supply West Cpast dealers\nwith all models. It is said the unit\nwill be erected near South Gate and\n'\u25a0Will cost more than $1,000,000.\nAmerican Locomotive Co.\u2014Alco\nProducts Division of this company re\nceived contract for construction of a\n,two-stage atmospheric and vacuum\nstill unit from Texas Co., subsidiary\nof Texas Corp. The project will cost\nabout $1,000,000, Alco\u2019s share of the\nbusiness being not far below the total\ncost.\nAmerican Stores Co.\u2014Sales four\nWeeks ended October 30 were up 2 per\ncent: 10 months up 0.4 per cent.\nGoldblatt Bros., Inc.\u2014Sales 39 weeks\nended October 30 were up 28.1 per\ncent.\nMagma Copper Co.\u2014Declared a\nyear-end dividend of $1.25 a share on\ncapital stock, payable December 15 to\nholders of record November 26, 1937.\nOn September 15, 1937, a dividend of\n60 cents a share was distributed.\nUnited Elastic Corp.\u2014Declared a\ndividend of 15 cents a share on capital\nstock, payable December 24 to holders\nof record December 3, 1937. On Sep\ntember 24, 1937, a dividend of 20 cents\na share was distributed.\nImperial Oil. Ltd.\u2014Declared an *y.\ntra dividend of 37Vi cents a share and\nregular semi-annual dividend of 25\n,cents a share, payable December 1 to\nholders of record November 17, 1937.\nA similar extra dividend was paid\nJune 1, 1937.\nInternational Petroleum Co.. Ltd.\nDeclared an extra dividend of 50 cents\nb share and regular semi-annual divi\ndend of 75 cents a share, payable De\ncember 1 to holders of record Novem\nber 19, 1937. On June 1, 1937, a sim\nilar extra dividend was paid.\nRollins Hosiery Mills, Inc.\u2014Declared\nAn initial dividend of $4 a share on\nconvertible stock, payable December\n16 to holders of record November 24,\nI9G7.\nHudson Motor Car Co.\u2014Common\nshare earnings, nine months ended\nSeptember 30, were 16 cents, against\n#1.30, before Federal taxes in like 1936\nI period.\nGreen Bay Western R. R.\u2014De\nclared a dividend of $5 a share on\ncapital stock, payable December 21 to\nholders of record December 8, 1937.\nLast previous payment was $2.50 a\nAhare on February 23, 1937. Interest\nof $50 was declared on each $1,000 of\nclass A debenture certificates and $15\non each $1,000 of class B debenture\ncertificates, both payable December 21,\n1937. Last previous payment on the\nClass A was $25 and on the class B\ndebenture certificates $10, both paid\nFebruary 23. 1937.\nWright-Hargreaves Mines, Ltd.\u2014\nDeclared an extra dividend of 5 cents\nA share and regular quarterly dividend\nof 10 cents a share, both payable Jan\nuary 3, 1938. to holders of record No\nvember 24, *1937. Similar extra dis\nbursement was made October 1, 1937.\n__\nCOMMODITY INDEX\nNEW YORK. Nov. jri.\u2014The Associated\nPress weighted wholesale price index of\n85 commodities today declined to 78.74.\nPrevious day. 78.84; week ago, 79.34;\nMonth ago. 83.04: year ago. 83.97.\nRange of recent years:\n1937. 1930. 1935. 1933-4.\nRigh 98.14 89,22 78.08 74.94\ntow 78.3.5 71.31 71.84 41.44\n(1926 average equals 100.)\nt Miscellaneous Markets.\nAdditional New York markets compiled\n\u00bby the Associated Press:\nWOOL TOPS\u2014Futures closed barely\nsteady. 15 to 25 lower. May. 82.0b; July,\n82.2b: October. 82.0b\nLEAD\u2014Futures closed steady. un\nchanged to 2 higher. Sales. 180.000\npounds. March. 5.05b; September. 5.05b.\nZinc futures closed quiet, unchanged\n\u2666o 5 higher No sales.\nCOCOA\u2014Futures closed barely steady.\n6 to 7 lower. Sales. 322 tons. Decem\nber. 5.85n; January. 5.84n; March. 5.83n;\nMay. 5.02.\nCOFFEE\u2014Spot quiet: Rio No. 7. 7n:\nSantos No. 4. 8>'2n. Cost and freight\nOfferings included Santos Bourbon 3s and\nAs at 7.20-50. Rio futures closed steady.\n3 to 7 higher. Sales. 4.000 bags. March.\n4 OOn: May, 4.50n: July. 4.44n: Septem\nber. 4.43n. Santos futures closed steady,\nA. to 15 higher. Sales. 18.000 bags.\nDecember. 6.son: March, fi.75-79: May,\n6.777: Julv. o.8o: September. 8.83n.\nCRUDE RUBBER\u2014Futures closed easy.\n81 to 35 lower. December, 14.77b: March.\nJ5.00-15.02: May. 15.12. Smoked ribbed\napot. 14.75n.\ns RAWHIDES\u2014Futures closed steady 4\nhigher to 5 lower. Sales. 1.800.000\nBounds December. 10.55b; March. 10.85\nBO; June, 11.20b.\nc b\u2014Bid. n\u2014Nominal.\nNEW YORK SUGAR.\nNEW YORK. Nov. 13 OPi.\u2014Raw sugar\nWag unchanged today at 3.35 for spots\nwyth no further sales reported.\nEarly steadiness in futures as a result\n*f further covering snd trade buying was\nfollowed by reactions under liquidation\nand hedge selling No. 3 contracts, after\nadvancing 1 to 2 points, closed 1 to 3\nnet lower as January eased from 2.40 to\n2.37 and March from 2.39 to 2.30. Sales,\nA.400 tons.\nIn the No. 4 gains of 44 point were\nlost, with March reacting from t. 14 to\n3r. 13V- and flnal Prices unchanged to 44\npoint net lower. Sales. 1,700 tons.\nRefined, as previously announced, was\nadvanced IQ points to 4.85 for fine granu\nlated by all refiners except one. who con\nttnued at 4.75 for prompt shipment.\ni ODD-LOT DEALINGS.\n$7 the Associated Press.\nThe Securities Commission reported yes\nterday these transactions by customers\nWith odd-lot dealers or specialists on the\nNew York Stock Exchange for November\n12: U.880 purchases involving 321.649\nshares; 8,783 sales Involving 246.748\nshares.\nWEEKLY SUMMARY OF THE NEW YORK CURB F1ARKET\nf\nWEEK ENDING SATURDAY, NOVEMBER 13, 1937.\nBy the Associated Press.\n193? Bet.\nHigh. Low. Stocks and Dividends. High. Low. Close. Cbie.\n64 14 Aero Sup Mf* B_ 3 24 24 4\n22 64 Ainsworth (.75*)_ 84 74 84\n4 4 Air Devices__ 14 14 14\n14 4 Air Inv war-... 4 4 4\n80 57 Ala Gt Sou (14k)_ 604 60 60 -4\n77 604 Ala Power pf (S)_ 62 58 62 +6\n'87 55 Ala Power pf (7)_ 714 68 704 +44\n164 6 Allied Products _ 124 124 124 -14\n264 16 Allied Prod A (1%)_ 18 18 18 -1\n1774 76 Alum Co Am _ 92 85 884 434\n1194 109 Alum Co pf (6) 112 111 112 4\n174 14 Aluminum Goods .75*_ 144 144 144 V*\n144 44 Alum Ind (.40)-..... 64 54 64 4\n140 65 Alum Ltd _ 70 66 70 +4\nVn 1194 Alum Ltd pf (6)_ 120 1194 120 -2\n324 74 Am Airlines_ 144 11